────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Overall Readiness: NEAR-READY (7/10)

The portfolio landing experience is architecturally sound, cleanly structured,
and performs well. Lint passes with zero errors. Build compiles successfully with
Turbopack. All six routes generate as static content. The foundational systems
(design tokens, animation, i18n, SEO) are in place.

Remaining gaps are concentrated in three areas:
  1. Visual identity — placeholder Lottie animation needs replacement
  2. Content — projects and creative works arrays are empty
  3. Minor DX / consistency issues (pnpm vs npm, deprecated file, i18n gaps)

None of the gaps are blockers for a soft v1 launch. The system is clean,
maintainable, and ready to iterate on.

Findings by severity:
  HIGH   ─  3
  MEDIUM ─  9
  LOW    ─ 12

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  1. ARCHITECTURE & COMPONENT DESIGN
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 9/10

Strengths:
  ✓ Clear, well-enforced directory contract:
      app/ → pages, layouts, metadata
      components/ → reusable, stateless UI primitives
      features/ → co-located feature modules
      lib/ → shared utilities and design token constants
      config/ → typed, validated environment and site configuration
      content/ → typed interfaces and static data arrays
      animations/ → raw Lottie JSON assets

  ✓ Feature-scoped animation isolation:
      features/landing/animation/ isolates useFadeUp hook and
      LandingVisualLayer from layout concerns. Swap-ready for 3D or
      alternative animation formats without touching LandingEntry.

  ✓ Barrel exports (index.ts) at every public boundary — clean import surfaces.

  ✓ Path alias @portfolio/* maps to ./src/* — consistent across all files.

  ✓ No circular dependencies observed.

  ✓ Server / client boundary is explicit:
      "use client" is present only where needed (interactive components).
      MainContent and LandingBackground are server-safe.

Findings:

  [MED] F-ARCH-01: src/lib/site.ts is deprecated but still present.
    File re-exports from @portfolio/config/site with a deprecation notice.
    Risk: dead code, import confusion.
    Action: Remove the file once consumers (if any) have migrated.
    Impact: Low (no consumers found in codebase).

  [LOW] F-ARCH-02: UI primitives (Center, Container, Section) do not use
    the clsx dependency that is already installed.
    Current: manual string concatenation with .filter(Boolean).join(" ")
    Preferred: clsx(base, className) — cleaner, handles edge cases.
    Action: Migrate in a single small PR.

  [LOW] F-ARCH-03: components/ui/ lacks an index.ts barrel export.
    Each component must be imported by full path. Adding a barrel is
    consistent with the pattern used in features/landing/ and
    components/animation/.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  2. RENDERING & PERFORMANCE
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 8/10

Strengths:
  ✓ All six routes are statically prerendered (○ Static). Zero server-side
    runtime cost at scale.
  ✓ Turbopack compilation is fast (4.3 s).
  ✓ Google Fonts loaded via next/font — zero layout shift, preloaded,
    self-hosted at build time.
  ✓ LottieAnimation is "use client" — no SSR hydration mismatch risk.
  ✓ Bundle analyzer available (npm run analyze / ANALYZE=true next build).
  ✓ AnimatePresence with mode="wait" prevents simultaneous animation renders.

Findings:

  [MED] F-PERF-01: Lottie animation is not lazy-loaded.
    Both instances (IdentityBlock avatar, LandingVisualLayer background) are
    eagerly loaded. The background animation is large and hidden from screen
    readers. Consider dynamic(() => import(...), { ssr: false }) wrapping for
    the background layer at minimum.

  [MED] F-PERF-02: og-image.png is referenced in metadata but resides in
    public/ without next/image optimization. At 1200×630, this image may be
    large. Verify it is properly compressed; consider serving a WebP variant.

  [LOW] F-PERF-03: No loading.tsx or suspense boundary on the page route.
    MainContent is an async server component — if content fetching is added
    later, there is no loading state. Proactive placement of loading.tsx
    would prevent a future performance regression.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  3. ANIMATION & MOTION SYSTEM
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 8/10

Strengths:
  ✓ Framer Motion v12 (latest major) — fully compatible with React 19.
  ✓ prefers-reduced-motion respected in all three animation sites:
      - useFadeUp hook returns static variants when motion is reduced.
      - EntryTrigger uses useReducedMotion from Framer Motion.
      - globals.css includes a @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) rule
        that disables all CSS animations/transitions globally as a safety net.
  ✓ LandingVisualLayer isolated — visual layer can be swapped independently
    of LandingBackground and LandingEntry.
  ✓ AnimatePresence handles unmount animations cleanly with mode="wait".
  ✓ Exit animation on landing stage (opacity: 0, scale: 1.04) creates a
    satisfying "zoom through" transition to main content.
  ✓ Staggered fade-up in IdentityBlock (delays: 0 / 0.15 / 0.28 s) produces
    a polished sequential reveal.

Findings:

  [HIGH] F-ANIM-01: placeholder.json is used as the Lottie animation for
    both the avatar and the background layer. This is a dev placeholder, not
    a brand asset. The animation is identical in both locations.
    Action: Replace with brand-specific Lottie assets before v1 release.
    Specifically: a personal avatar / logo animation for IdentityBlock, and
    an abstract atmospheric animation for LandingVisualLayer.

  [LOW] F-ANIM-02: EntryTrigger animation (breathing line + text) uses
    hardcoded repeat: Infinity. This is correct UX but should be verified
    that it does not contribute to layout thrashing on low-end devices.
    Consider will-change: opacity on the animated span as a micro-opt.

  [LOW] F-ANIM-03: LandingEntry exit transition duration (0.5 s) and main
    content entrance duration (0.55 s) slightly overlap. With AnimatePresence
    mode="wait" this is safe, but the cumulative perceived transition time is
    ~1.05 s which may feel long on repeat visits. Consider persisting the
    entered state in sessionStorage to skip the entry animation on refresh.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  4. STYLING & LAYOUT SYSTEM
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 9/10

Strengths:
  ✓ Tailwind v4 with @theme inline — modern, performant, no JIT lag.
  ✓ Design tokens are dual-defined:
      CSS custom properties in globals.css :root (consumed by Tailwind + CSS)
      TypeScript constants in lib/tokens.ts (consumed by JS/Framer Motion)
  ✓ Semantic token names (--text-primary, --accent, --border) — not raw
    color values in class names.
  ✓ Responsive breakpoints applied consistently (sm:, md: suffixes).
  ✓ overflow-x: hidden on both html and body prevents horizontal scroll
    caused by oversized Lottie animations.
  ✓ box-sizing: border-box on all elements.
  ✓ color-scheme: dark — correct for a dark-only theme; prevents browser
    UI flash.
  ✓ Typography scale fully defined (xs through 5xl) with responsive scaling
    for h1–h3 on mobile.
  ✓ :focus-visible ring using accent color — accessible and visually clean.

Findings:

  [MED] F-STYLE-01: No light mode support.
    Only dark theme is defined. If a user has prefers-color-scheme: light,
    the dark theme is still applied. This is acceptable for v1 but should be
    a documented decision. Add a comment in globals.css stating this is
    intentional.

  [LOW] F-STYLE-02: Section component applies py-12 sm:py-16 padding.
    MainContent wraps Section inside Center with additional py-16. This may
    result in double-padding on some viewport sizes. Audit padding once real
    content sections are added.

  [LOW] F-STYLE-03: --border: #1f1f1f is very dark (minimal contrast against
    --surface: #111111). Fine for subtle dividers but will be nearly invisible
    if used for interactive element borders. Flag for design review when
    interactive cards or inputs are added.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  5. UX & INTERACTION DESIGN
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 7/10

Strengths:
  ✓ Two-stage landing sequence (identity → content) creates a deliberate,
    premium first impression.
  ✓ Click-anywhere-to-enter pattern is intuitive and satisfying.
  ✓ EntryTrigger provides visual and textual affordance (breathing line +
    "Click anywhere, or press Enter / Space").
  ✓ Keyboard support: Enter and Space trigger entry.
  ✓ Landscape/short viewport handled: EntryTrigger hidden at max-height:500px,
    and pb-16 wrapper collapses via @media(max-height:500px):pb-0.
  ✓ cursor-pointer on the full landing stage — correct for click affordance.

Findings:

  [MED] F-UX-01: No skip-to-main-content link.
    Screen reader and keyboard-only users who tab through the landing stage
    cannot skip to the main content stage. Add a visually hidden skip link
    at the top of the document.

  [MED] F-UX-02: Entered state is ephemeral (React useState).
    Refreshing the page resets the entry animation. Users who have already
    seen the landing see it again every visit. Consider persisting
    entered=true in sessionStorage so the entry is shown once per browser
    session.

  [MED] F-UX-03: MainContent is "coming soon" with empty content arrays.
    projects[] and creativeWorks[] are empty. The main content stage shows
    only the name, tagline, and footer. This is functional but thin for v1.
    Action: Populate at least one project entry before release.

  [LOW] F-UX-04: EntryTrigger label text is hardcoded English.
    "Click anywhere, or press Enter / Space" is not i18n'd. If additional
    locales are added, this will break consistency. Add to en.json and
    reference via useTranslations.

  [LOW] F-UX-05: No 404 / not-found page customized.
    Only /_not-found (default Next.js) is present. A branded not-found page
    would improve overall polish.

