Findings:

  [HIGH] F-DEP-01: next@16.2.3 is a non-standard version.
    The public Next.js stable channel is 14.x / 15.x. Version 16 is not
    yet publicly released (or is a pre-release). Ensure this is intentional
    and that the package source is trustworthy. Verify compatibility with
    eslint-config-next@16.2.3 and @next/bundle-analyzer@16.2.3 (aligned).
    Risk: API instability if this is a canary/pre-release build.

  [MED] F-DEP-02: pnpm-lock.yaml present but package manager is inconsistent.
    vercel.json: installCommand = "pnpm install --frozen-lockfile"
    .github/workflows/ci.yml: uses pnpm/action-setup@v5
    README / package.json scripts: npm
    Memory note: pnpm-workspace.yaml lacks a packages field.
    Action: Standardize on one package manager. If pnpm, fix workspace config.
    If npm, update vercel.json and CI workflow.

  [LOW] F-DEP-03: No test framework installed.
    No jest, vitest, playwright, or @testing-library/* in dependencies.
    The project has zero test coverage. Acceptable for v1 but should be
    planned for milestone 2.

  [LOW] F-DEP-04: No pre-commit hooks (no husky, no lint-staged).
    Formatting and linting are not enforced at commit time. CI catches issues
    but only after push. Add husky + lint-staged if team grows beyond solo.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  7. CODE QUALITY & MAINTAINABILITY
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 8/10

Strengths:
  ✓ TypeScript strict mode enabled (strict: true in tsconfig.json).
  ✓ ESLint: next/core-web-vitals + next/typescript + prettier — zero lint
    errors on current codebase.
  ✓ Prettier configured — consistent formatting.
  ✓ Content types are well-defined and documented (types.ts).
  ✓ Functions are small and focused — no god components detected.
  ✓ Props interfaces are defined locally with JSDoc on non-obvious fields.
  ✓ useCallback in LandingEntry.handleEnter uses functional update correctly
    to avoid stale closure issues.

Findings:

  [MED] F-QUAL-01: i18n key duplication.
    IdentityBlock.name == MainContent.name == "Alan Szmyt"
    IdentityBlock.tagline == MainContent.tagline == "Software engineer..."
    These are semantically the same string stored under two keys. Consolidate
    into a shared namespace (e.g., "Author") to avoid divergence.

  [MED] F-QUAL-02: unstable_retry prop in error pages.
    error.tsx and global-error.tsx use the prop name unstable_retry.
    This indicates a Next.js API that is not yet stable. Monitor for
    breaking changes when upgrading Next.js.

  [LOW] F-QUAL-03: src/lib/site.ts export is marked @deprecated.
    No consumers of this file were found in the codebase. The file should be
    deleted to avoid confusion. If it was added for backwards compatibility
    with an external consumer, document that explicitly.

  [LOW] F-QUAL-04: LandingEntry.tsx is marked "use client" but contains
    the only <main> semantic element in the landing stage. This is correct
    but means the main landmark is rendered client-side. Consider whether
    the interactive shell (motion, state) could be extracted so that the
    <main> element is SSR-rendered.

  [LOW] F-QUAL-05: i18n messages for LandingEntry.comingSoon ("Main content
    coming soon.") will become stale once real content is added. Plan to
    remove this key when MainContent is fully populated.

────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  8. ACCESSIBILITY & SEMANTICS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

SCORE: 8/10

Strengths:
  ✓ lang attribute set on <html> from next-intl locale — correct.
  ✓ aria-hidden="true" on all decorative SVGs (Footer social icons).
  ✓ aria-hidden="true" on LandingBackground — correct for decorative layer.
  ✓ role="button" + tabIndex={0} + aria-label on EntryTrigger.
  ✓ onKeyDown handles both Enter and Space on EntryTrigger.
  ✓ aria-expanded on DebugPanel toggle.
  ✓ role="region" + aria-label on DebugPanel content area.
  ✓ aria-label on all three social link anchors in Footer.
  ✓ :focus-visible ring defined in globals.css using --accent color.
  ✓ prefers-reduced-motion handled at both CSS and JS/Framer Motion levels.

Findings:

  [HIGH] F-A11Y-01: Duplicate <h1> elements across component states.
    IdentityBlock renders <h1>{t("IdentityBlock.name")}</h1>.
    MainContent renders <h1>{t("MainContent.name")}</h1>.
    While AnimatePresence unmounts one before mounting the other, both
    stages exist in the DOM transiently during the transition. Verify with
    automated a11y tooling (axe) that no h1 overlap occurs. In MainContent,
    the name heading may be better expressed as an h2 if it is a subheading
    below a page-level h1 elsewhere.

  [MED] F-A11Y-02: No skip-to-main-content link (same as F-UX-01).
    Keyboard-only users must tab through the entire landing stage UI before
    reaching main content. A visually hidden <a href="#main-content"> at
    the start of the document is the standard solution.

  [MED] F-A11Y-03: LottieAnimation has no accessible label or description.
    The Lottie animation in IdentityBlock is the visual avatar/hero element.
    Without alt text or aria-label, screen reader users receive no context.
    Wrap in a <figure> with <figcaption> or add role="img" aria-label="..."
    to the container div.

  [LOW] F-A11Y-04: aria-label="love" on the ♥ span in Footer.
    While creative, this is not a standard ARIA pattern. The ♥ character
    followed by the label creates redundant announcement ("heart love").
    Consider aria-label="heart" or simply wrapping in <abbr title="love">♥</abbr>.

  [LOW] F-A11Y-05: rel="noopener noreferrer" is correct on Footer external
    links. No issues. (Noting as verified.)

  [LOW] F-A11Y-06: No color contrast audit performed programmatically.
    Visual inspection suggests --text-muted (#7a7a7a) on --background (#0a0a0a)
    may not meet WCAG AA (4.5:1) for body text. The muted color is used in
    Footer copy and EntryTrigger hint text. Run an automated contrast check
    (e.g., axe DevTools) before release.

